Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Earth processes have not changed over time.
Sent 2: The way things happen now is the same way things happened in the past.
Sent 3: Mountains grow and mountains slowly wear away.
Sent 4: The same process is at work the same as it was billions of years ago.
Sent 5: As the environment changes, living creatures adapt.
Sent 6: They change over time.
Sent 7: Some organisms may not be able to adapt.
Sent 8: They become extinct.
Sent 9: Becoming extinct means they die out completely.
Sent 10: Some geologists study the history of the Earth.
Sent 11: They want to learn about Earths past.
Sent 12: They use clues from rocks and fossils.
Sent 13: They use these clues to make sense of events.
Sent 14: The goal is to place things in the order they happened.
Sent 15: They also want to know how long it took for those events to happen.
Answer.Answer-1: they become extinct and die out
Answer.Answer-2: They look for clues in rocks and fossils to make sense of events and figure out how they happened.
Answer.Answer-3: Organisms adapt but some may not be able to and go extinct.
Answer.Question-1: What happens when some organisms are not able to adapt and what does it mean for them?
Answer.Question-2: How do geologist study the history of the earth?
Answer.Question-3: What happens when the environment changes?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Leaves are the keys not only to plant life but to virtually all life on land.
Sent 2: The primary role of leaves is to collect sunlight.
Sent 3: This sunlight is needed for the plant to make food.
Sent 4: Leaves vary in size, shape, and how they are arranged on stems.
Sent 5: You can see examples of different types of leaves in Figure 3.19.
Sent 6: Each type of leaf is well suited for the plants environment.
Sent 7: It maximizes light exposure while conserving water.
Sent 8: They are also reduces wind resistance.
Sent 9: Leaves also benefit the plant in some other way in its particular habitat.
Sent 10: For example, some leaves are divided into many smaller leaflets.
Sent 11: This reduces wind resistance and water loss.
Sent 12: Leaves are basically factories for photosynthesis.
Sent 13: A factory has specialized machines to produce a product.
Sent 14: In a leaf, the \machines\ are the chloroplasts.
Sent 15: A factory is connected to a transportation system that supplies it with raw materials and carries away the finished product.
Sent 16: In a leaf, transport is carried out by veins containing vascular tissue.
Sent 17: Veins carry water and minerals to the cells of leaves.
Sent 18: They carry away dissolved sugar.
Answer.Answer-1: For food
Answer.Answer-2: Reduces wind resistance and water loss
Answer.Answer-3: Photosynthesis
Answer.Question-1: What is the reason leaves primarily collect sunlight?
Answer.Question-2: Why are some leaves divided into smaller leaflets?
Answer.Question-3: A factory has specialized machines to produce a product and leaves basically have factories for what?
Answer.Question-4: Factories have specialized machines to do the work and in leaves the machines are called?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: There have been many organisms that have lived in Earths past.
Sent 2: Only a tiny number of them became fossils.
Sent 3: Still, scientists learn a lot from fossils.
Sent 4: Fossils are our best clues about the history of life on Earth.
Sent 5: Fossils provide evidence about life on Earth.
Sent 6: They tell us that life on Earth has changed over time.
Sent 7: Fossils in younger rocks look like animals and plants that are living today.
Sent 8: Fossils in older rocks are less like living organisms.
Sent 9: Fossils can tell us about where the organism lived.
Sent 10: Was it land or marine?
Sent 11: Fossils can even tell us if the water was shallow or deep.
Sent 12: Fossils can even provide clues to ancient climates.
Answer.Answer-1: They tell us life on Earth has changed over time, tell us where an organism lived, and give climate clues.
Answer.Answer-2: Younger ones look like animals and plants alive today but older ones are less like living organisms.
Answer.Answer-3: Fossils
Answer.Question-1: What are some things that Fossils can tell us?
Answer.Question-2: How do fossils differ from younger rocks to older rocks?
Answer.Question-3: What mentioned item provides information about the history of life on Earth, gives a snapshot of life over time, and can offer clues to climate change?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: For thousands of years, people have found fossils.
Sent 2: The fossils caused curiosity about Earths past.
Sent 3: How did these organisms live?
Sent 4: What type of world did they live in?
Sent 5: Fossils can tell us a lot about Earths history.
Sent 6: In ancient times, fossils inspired myths and stories.
Sent 7: These stories included tales of monsters and other incredible creatures.
Sent 8: What type of creature do you know that could inspire such stories?
Sent 9: Of course, dinosaur fossils were once mistaken for dragons bones.
Sent 10: Two thousand years ago, people discovered fossils in China.
Sent 11: At the time, they were thought to be dragon bones.
Sent 12: We know now that these were not bones, but fossils.
Sent 13: So what is the difference?
Answer.Answer-1: People been finding fossils for thousands of years and they inspired myths and stories.
Answer.Answer-2: The stories contained monster and dinosaur bones were mistaken for dragons.
Answer.Answer-3: They were found in China 2 thousand years ago and thought to have been bones.
Answer.Question-1: How long have people been finding fossils and what did they inspire?
Answer.Question-2: What did these stories consist of?
Answer.Question-3: How long ago and in what country were the first documented fossils found?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: When land is cleared, habitats are lost.
Sent 2: It may be cleared for agriculture.
Sent 3: It may also be used for building new homes or businesses.
Sent 4: Within the past 100 years, the amount of land used for agriculture has almost doubled.
Sent 5: Land used for grazing cattle has more than doubled.
Sent 6: Many wetlands have also been lost to agriculture (Figure 3.25).
Sent 7: The U.S. has lost almost all the natural tall-grass prairies.
Sent 8: Thee areas of tall thick grass have virtually disappeared.
Sent 9: These areas of land had thick fertile soil.
Sent 10: Their grasses had very deep root systems.
Sent 11: These deep and thick roots reduced the amount of soil erosion.
Sent 12: They also were home to many plants and animals.
Sent 13: Prairies were wonderful places.
Sent 14: They were home to colorful flowers, prairie dogs, and herds of bison.
Answer.Answer-1: It may then be used for agriculture, homes or businesses.
Answer.Answer-2: The loss of native plants with deep root systems increases the amount of soil erosion.
Answer.Answer-3: Prairies
Answer.Question-1: What opportunities come from the loss of habitat due to clearing land?
Answer.Question-2: How does the clearing of wetlands impact an area's rate of soil erosion?
Answer.Question-3: Once home to colorful flowers, prairie dogs, and herds of bison, what types of places are cleared for new homes and businesses?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Electricity can be very dangerous.
Sent 2: To reduce the risk of injury, safety features are built into electric circuits and devices.
Sent 3: You might have noticed some of these in your home.
Sent 4: They include three-prong plugs, circuit breakers, and GFCI outlets.
Sent 5: Each feature is described and illustrated in Table 1.4.
Sent 6: Electric Safety Feature Three-Prong Plug Description A three-prong plug is generally used on metal appli- ances.
Sent 7: The two flat prongs carry the current.
Sent 8: The round prong is for safety.
Sent 9: It connects with a wire inside the outlet.
Sent 10: This wire connects to the ground.
Sent 11: By redirecting the current it can pass into the ground.
Sent 12: The ground is where it can be harmlessly absorbed.
Sent 13: Circuit Breaker A circuit breaker is another safety feature.
Sent 14: The circuit breaker automatically opens a circuit if too much cur- rent flows through it.
Sent 15: This could happen if too many electric devices are plugged in.
Sent 16: It can also happen if there is an electric short.
Sent 17: Once the problem is resolved, the circuit breaker can be switched back on.
Sent 18: Once switched back on, the circuit is closed.
Answer.Answer-1: three-prong plugs, circuit breakers, and GFCI outlets.
Answer.Answer-2: it can be harmlessly absorbed
Answer.Answer-3: circuit breaker automatically opens a circuit if too much cur- rent flows through it
Answer.Question-1: What safety features are built into electric circuits and devices?
Answer.Question-2: By redirecting the current into the ground, what happens?
Answer.Question-3: What happens when there is an electrical short?
Answer.Question-4: Once the problem is solved what happens to the circuit?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Abrasion is another type of weathering.
Sent 2: Like ice wedging, it is a form of mechanical weathering.
Sent 3: Like ice wedging, abrasion does not change the rock into another type of rock.
Sent 4: With abrasion, one rock or piece of sediment bumps against another rock.
Sent 5: Rocks dont normally roll around on their own, so why do they move?
Sent 6: There are a couple of reasons a rock may move.
Sent 7: Gravity can cause rocks to move.
Sent 8: They may roll downhill or fall off a cliff.
Sent 9: As they roll down a hill, they bump into each other.
Sent 10: Maybe a moving rock hits a rock that is not moving at the bottom of the hill.
Sent 11: Moving water causes rocks and sediment to move.
Sent 12: Rocks are bounced along the bottom and bump against one another (Figure 2.37).
Sent 13: As they collide, they begin to chip away at each other.
Sent 14: Angular rocks become more rounded with each collision.
Sent 15: Strong winds cause abrasion.
Sent 16: The wind carries sediment.
Sent 17: This sediment is thrown against other rocky surfaces by the wind.
Sent 18: It is like sand-blasting a rock.
Answer.Answer-1: Both are types of mechanical weathering.
Answer.Answer-2: Gravity, water and winds
Answer.Answer-3: Ice welding changes rocks into other types of rock, abrasion does not.
Answer.Answer-5: It acts like a sand-blaster, changing the rocks shapes.
Answer.Question-1: How is abrasion and ice welding similar?
Answer.Question-2: Which three phenomena can change the shape of rocks due to abrasion?
Answer.Question-3: How is ice wedging different from abrasion?
Answer.Question-4: As rocks collide what happens to their shape?
Answer.Question-5: How does sediment affect rock surfaces?

Sent 12: Rocks are bounced along the bottom and bump against one another (Figure 2.37).
Sent 13: As they collide, they begin to chip away at each other.
Sent 14: Angular rocks become more rounded with each collision.
Sent 15: Strong winds cause abrasion.
Sent 16: The wind carries sediment.
Sent 17: This sediment is thrown against other rocky surfaces by the wind.
Sent 18: It is like sand-blasting a rock.
Answer.Answer-1: abrasion and ice wedging
Answer.Answer-2: The wind carries sediment that is thrown against other rocky surfaces, acting like sand-blasting a rock.
Answer.Answer-3: one rock or piece of sediment bumps against another rock when they roll down a hill, or moving water forces them against one another or against other sediment.
Answer.Question-1: What are two types of weathering?
Answer.Question-2: How does strong wind cause abrasion?
Answer.Question-3: What causes abrasion?

Answer.Answer-2: SKELETAL SYSTEM

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Sound waves are mechanical waves.
Sent 2: They can travel only through matter.
Sent 3: They cannot travel through empty space.
Sent 4: This was demonstrated in the 1600s by a scientist named Robert Boyle.
Sent 5: Boyle placed a ticking clock in a sealed glass jar.
Sent 6: The clock could be heard ticking through the air and glass of the jar.
Sent 7: Then Boyle pumped the air out of the jar.
Sent 8: The clock was still running, but the ticking could not be heard.
Sent 9: Thats because the sound couldnt travel without air particles to transfer the sound energy.
Sent 10: Is there any other place where sound cannot be heard?
Sent 11: Here is a hint: is there any other place that does not have air molecules?
Sent 12: Thats right, in space sound cannot be transferred.
Sent 13: So can astronauts hear each other?
Sent 14: Yes, they can, because they are in enclosed space stations or pressurized suits.In both cases, they are surrounded by air molecules.
Sent 15: If they left their space ship and did not use their electronics, they would not be able to hear each other.
Sent 16: Next time you watch a science fiction movie, think about this factoid.
Sent 17: When spaceships are destroyed by hostile alien beings, there would be no sound heard.
Sent 18: Sound waves can travel through many kinds of matter.
Answer.Answer-1: They are in enclosed space stations or pressurized suits which means they are surrounded by air molecules
Answer.Answer-2: Robert Boyle
Answer.Answer-3: in space sound cannot be transferred
Answer.Question-1: Why can astronauts here each other even if sound cannot be transferred in space ?
Answer.Question-2: Which scientist demonstrated that sound waves cannot travel through empty space by placing a ticking clock in a sealed glass jar ?
Answer.Question-3: In a science fiction movie when aliens destroy a spaceship why would there be no sound heard ?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Sound waves are mechanical waves.
Sent 2: They can travel only through matter.
Sent 3: They cannot travel through empty space.
Sent 4: This was demonstrated in the 1600s by a scientist named Robert Boyle.
Sent 5: Boyle placed a ticking clock in a sealed glass jar.
Sent 6: The clock could be heard ticking through the air and glass of the jar.
Sent 7: Then Boyle pumped the air out of the jar.
Sent 8: The clock was still running, but the ticking could not be heard.
Sent 9: Thats because the sound couldnt travel without air particles to transfer the sound energy.
Sent 10: Is there any other place where sound cannot be heard?
Sent 11: Here is a hint: is there any other place that does not have air molecules?
Sent 12: Thats right, in space sound cannot be transferred.
Sent 13: So can astronauts hear each other?
Sent 14: Yes, they can, because they are in enclosed space stations or pressurized suits.In both cases, they are surrounded by air molecules.
Sent 15: If they left their space ship and did not use their electronics, they would not be able to hear each other.
Sent 16: Next time you watch a science fiction movie, think about this factoid.
Sent 17: When spaceships are destroyed by hostile alien beings, there would be no sound heard.
Sent 18: Sound waves can travel through many kinds of matter.
Answer.Answer-1: Sound waves can travel only through matter and not through empty space.
Answer.Answer-2: Boyle placed a ticking clock in a sealed glass jar. The clock could be heard ticking through the air and glass of the jar but after Boyle pumped the air out of the jar, the clock was still running, but the ticking could not be heard.
Answer.Answer-3: They are in enclosed space stations or pressurized suits.In both cases, they are surrounded by air molecules, but if they left their space ship and did not use their electronics, they would not be able to hear each other.
Answer.Question-1: How do sound waves travel?
Answer.Question-2: How did Robert Boyle prove how sound waves travel?
Answer.Question-3: How do astronauts hear each other?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: A friend whispers to you in class.
Sent 2: You can barely hear them.
Sent 3: To hear better you have to lean very close to hear what hes saying.
Sent 4: Later that day, your friend shouts to you across the football field.
Sent 5: Now his voice is very loud.
Sent 6: You have no problem hearing him clearly even though hes many meters away.
Sent 7: Obviously, sounds can vary in loudness.
Sent 8: Loudness refers to how loud or soft a sound seems to a listener.
Sent 9: The loudness of sound is related to the intensity of sound.
Sent 10: Intensity is a measure of the amount of energy in sound waves.
Sent 11: The unit of intensity is the decibel (dB).
Sent 12: The intensity of sound waves determines the loudness of sounds, but what determines intensity?
Sent 13: Intensity is a function of two factors.
Sent 14: First, the amount of energy contained in the sound waves.
Sent 15: Second, how far away you are from the source of the sound.
Sent 16: Remember that sound waves start at a source of vibrations.
Sent 17: Those sound waves spread out from the source in all directions.
Sent 18: The farther the sound waves travel away from the source, the more spread out their energy becomes.
Answer.Answer-1: when we shout and when we whisper
Answer.Answer-2: First, the amount of energy contained in the sound waves. Second, how far away you are from the source of the sound.
Answer.Answer-3: Loudness is how loud something seems to the listener, while intensity is a measure of the amount of energy in sound waves.
Answer.Question-1: What are some examples of sound carrying varying loudness?
Answer.Question-2: Intensity is the function of what two factors?
Answer.Question-3: What is the difference between loudness and intensity?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Both conduction and convection transfer energy through matter.
Sent 2: Radiation is the only way of transferring energy that doesnt require matter.
Sent 3: Radiation is the transfer of energy by waves.
Sent 4: These waves can travel through empty space.
Sent 5: When these waves reach objects, they transfer energy to the objects.
Sent 6: This causes them to warm up.
Sent 7: This is how the Suns energy reaches Earth and heats its surface (see Figure 1.27).
Sent 8: Radiation is also how thermal energy from a campfire warms people nearby.
Sent 9: You might be surprised to learn that all objects radiate thermal energy.
Sent 10: This even includes you.
Sent 11: In fact, when a room is full of people, it may feel noticeably warmer.
Sent 12: This is because of all the thermal energy the people radiate!
Answer.Answer-1: Both are warmer because of thermal energy. The sun's radiation hearts the earth and the people radiate heat as well.
Answer.Answer-2: The waves travel through space to objects, transferring energy to those objects and causing them to warm up.
Answer.Answer-3: Radiation doesn't require matter
Answer.Question-1: How is the way the sun heats the earth and why a room filled with people being warmer similar?
Answer.Question-2: How does radiation work?
Answer.Question-3: How is radiation different from conduction and convection?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph

Sent 8: The fluid may be a liquid or a gas.

Sent 11: These loops are called convection currents.
Sent 12: Radiation is the transfer of thermal energy by waves.
Sent 13: These waves can travel through empty space.
Sent 14: When the waves reach objects, the heat is transferred to the objects.
Sent 15: Radiation is how the Sun warms the Earths surface.

Answer.Answer-2: A conductor because insulators are bad conductors of heat.
Answer.Answer-3: No, it moves through a fluid.

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Light rays strike a reflecting surface.
Sent 2: They are then reflected back.
Sent 3: You can predict the angle of the reflected light.
Sent 4: Imagine a ball bouncing off a surface.
Sent 5: Light can do the same thing.
Sent 6: That is, assuming the surface is shiny.
Sent 7: So how do you know where light will go after it strikes a shiny surface?
Sent 8: It depends on how the light initially strikes the shiny object.
Sent 9: Light does not always go straight toward a surface.
Sent 10: Therefore, not all light bounces straight back.
Sent 11: Sometimes, light can hit a surface at an angle.
Sent 12: The angle at which it strikes the surface tells us how it will bounce off.
Sent 13: While light is different to a ball, they react in a similar manner.
Sent 14: Many sports rely on knowledge of reflection.
Sent 15: Pool players know a lot about reflection.
Sent 16: They take great care when they strike the pool ball.
Sent 17: They need it to go to a certain place.
Sent 18: They know the angle it will hit the side of the pool table.
Answer.Answer-1: No. Like a ball bounces off a surface (Sent. 4) Light can also bounce off a surface. (Sent. 5) But only if it is a shiny surface. (Sent. 6)
Answer.Answer-2: The angle. The angle at which light surface determines how it will bounce off. (Sent 12) A ball behaves similarly to light when it hits a surface. (Sent 13)
Answer.Answer-3: Yes. Pool players know a lot about reflection. (Sent. 15)  They know the angle the ball will hit the sides of the pool table. (Sent. 18) They need it to go to a certain place. (Sent. 17)
Answer.Question-1: Does light always bounce off the surface it hits?
Answer.Question-2: What determines how a ball will bounce off a surface?
Answer.Question-3: Do pool players use the principles of reflection to get a ball to go to a certain place?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph

Sent 14: They drip to the floor of the cave.
Sent 15: It is there the minerals in the water harden to form stalagmites.
Sent 16: A stalagmite is a more rounded mineral deposit.
Sent 17: It forms on the floor of a cave.
Sent 18: Both types of formations grow in size as water keeps dripping and more minerals are deposited.

Answer.Answer-2: holes or caves can form
Answer.Answer-3: when minerals from the water do not dissolve they build up on the ceiling of caves
Answer.Answer-4: stalactites drip minerals to the cave floor the minerals then harden
Answer.Question-1: How does flowing water cause change?
Answer.Question-2: What happens when large areas of rocks dissolve?
Answer.Question-3: How is a stalactite formed?
Answer.Question-4: How do stalagmites form?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Plate boundaries are where two plates meet.
Sent 2: These are dynamic areas.
Sent 3: Most geologic activity takes place at plate boundaries.
Sent 4: As plates interact, they cause many of the large features we see on Earths surface.
Sent 5: AS plates Interact they can cause volcanoes, earthquakes.
Sent 6: They can even cause mountain ranges to form.
Sent 7: Plates can interact in different ways.
Sent 8: Plates can move away from each other.
Sent 9: They can move toward each other.
Sent 10: Finally, they can slide past each other.
Sent 11: These are the three types of plate boundaries: At divergent plate boundaries the two plates move away from each other.
Sent 12: At convergent plate boundaries the two plates move towards each other.
Sent 13: At transform plate boundaries the two plates slip past each other.
Sent 14: The features created vary by the boundary type.
Sent 15: They also vary by the type of crust at the boundary.
Answer.Answer-1: The three types of plate boundaries are divergent, convergent and transform plate boundaries.
Answer.Answer-2: They can create volcanoes, earthquakes and sometimes new mountain ranges.
Answer.Answer-3: They can move away from each other, move towards each other or slide past each other.
Answer.Question-1: What are the three types of plate boundaries?
Answer.Question-2: What earth changes occur when plates interact?
Answer.Question-3: How do plates move when they interact with each other?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph

Sent 13: They divide the Earth from North to South.
Sent 14: Lines of longitude run from north to south.
Sent 15: They divide the Earth from East to West.
Sent 16: Zero longitude runs through Greenwich, England.
Sent 17: You may have heard the term, Greenwich Mean Time, or GMT.
Sent 18: The system of latitude and longitude works well for objects that do not move.

Answer.Answer-2: A latitude and longitude grid centered on a reference point.
Answer.Answer-3: North to South.
Answer.Answer-4: To pinpoint a feature they are studying.

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.

Sent 6: How can we describe a direction?
Sent 7: The most common way is by using a compass.
Sent 8: A compass is a device with a floating needle (Figure 2.1).
Sent 9: The needle is a small magnet.
Sent 10: The needle aligns itself with the Earths magnetic field.
Sent 11: The compass needle always points to magnetic north.
Sent 12: If you have a compass and you find north.
Sent 13: You can then know any other direction.
Sent 14: See the directions, such as east, south, west, etc., on a compass rose.
Sent 15: The Earth has two poles.
Sent 16: It has a magnetic north pole.
Sent 17: It also has a geographic north pole.
Sent 18: These two poles are close to each other but not the exact same place.
Answer.Answer-1: the directions on a compass, north,south,east,west
Answer.Answer-2: magnetic, and geographic
Answer.Answer-3: its a magnet it always points north
Answer.Question-1: How do we describe direction?
Answer.Question-2: What are the earths two poles?
Answer.Question-3: what is the floating needle in a compass and which way does it point?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Renewable Energy Resource Sunlight Sunlight can be used to heat homes.
Sent 2: It can also be used to produce electricity.
Sent 3: This conversion is made possible by solar cells.
Sent 4: However, solar energy may not always be practical.
Sent 5: Some areas are just too cloudy.
Sent 6: Example Solar panels on the roof of this house generate enough electricity to supply a familys needs.
Sent 7: Moving Water Falling water can have a lot of energy.
Sent 8: Its energy can be converted into kinetic energy.
Sent 9: This energy can turn a turbine and generate electricity.
Sent 10: The water may fall naturally over a waterfall or flow through a dam.
Sent 11: A drawback of dams is that they flood land upstream.
Sent 12: They can also reduce water flow downstream.
Sent 13: Either effect may harm ecosystems.
Sent 14: Wind Wind is moving air.
Sent 15: It has kinetic energy that can do work.
Sent 16: Wind turbines change the kinetic energy of the wind to electrical energy.
Sent 17: Only certain areas of the world get enough steady wind.
Sent 18: Many people also think that wind turbines are noisy and not very nice to look at.
Answer.Answer-1: solar, water, and wind energy
Answer.Answer-2: Electricity
Answer.Answer-3: flooding upstream, not enough water downstream.
Answer.Question-1: What are some forms of renewable energy listed in the paragraph?
Answer.Question-2: What can these forms of energy be used to produce?
Answer.Question-3: What is the drawback of kinetic energy from hydro power?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph

Sent 12: There is a limited supply.
Sent 13: Someday, we will run out, so then what?
Sent 14: At current rates of use, coal will last about 300 years.
Sent 15: Petroleum will be used up in just a few decades.

Answer.Answer-2: Coal, oil,  and petroleum
Answer.Answer-3: Having your favorite drink and then suddenly not being able to refill it because it didn't exist anymore.

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: As food is pushed along, it undergoes digestion.
Sent 2: Digestion is the process of breaking down food into nutrients.
Sent 3: There are two types of digestion: mechanical digestion and chemical digestion.
Sent 4: Mechanical digestion occurs when large chunks are turned into smaller chucks.
Sent 5: Perhaps not surprisingly, this happen when you chew your food.
Sent 6: Once you swallow the food, your stomach also does some of this work.
Sent 7: Chemical digestion occurs when food is broken down into useful nutrients.
Sent 8: This is a chemical process that begins as you start to chew your food.
Sent 9: The saliva in your mouth starts this process.
Sent 10: Once you swallow, the acid in your stomach further breaks down food.
Sent 11: From the stomach, the foods moves into the small intestine.
Sent 12: In the small intestines, another set of chemicals goes to work.
Sent 13: Are you surprised?
Sent 14: Your small intestine, and not your stomach, does most of the work!
Answer.Answer-1: DIGESTION
Answer.Answer-2: MECHANICAL AND CHEMICAL

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: As food is pushed along, it undergoes digestion.
Sent 2: Digestion is the process of breaking down food into nutrients.
Sent 3: There are two types of digestion: mechanical digestion and chemical digestion.
Sent 4: Mechanical digestion occurs when large chunks are turned into smaller chucks.
Sent 5: Perhaps not surprisingly, this happen when you chew your food.
Sent 6: Once you swallow the food, your stomach also does some of this work.
Sent 7: Chemical digestion occurs when food is broken down into useful nutrients.
Sent 8: This is a chemical process that begins as you start to chew your food.
Sent 9: The saliva in your mouth starts this process.
Sent 10: Once you swallow, the acid in your stomach further breaks down food.
Sent 11: From the stomach, the foods moves into the small intestine.
Sent 12: In the small intestines, another set of chemicals goes to work.
Sent 13: Are you surprised?
Sent 14: Your small intestine, and not your stomach, does most of the work!
Answer.Answer-1: The process of breaking down food into nutrients, through mechanical and chemical means
Answer.Answer-2: Occurs when large chunks are turned into smaller chucks, done by chewing
Answer.Answer-3: Occurs when food is broken down into useful nutrients, it occurs in the stomach and mouth.
Answer.Answer-5: Saliva and acid in the stomach

Answer.Question-2: What is mechanical digestion?
Answer.Question-3: What is chemical digestion, and where does it occur?
Answer.Question-4: What organs help digestion?
Answer.Question-5: What bodily fluids aide in digestion?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: The digestive system is the body system that digests food.
Sent 2: It digest food in two ways, mechanically and chemically.
Sent 3: Both help in the process of turning food into nutrients.
Sent 4: The digestive system also eliminates solid food waste.
Sent 5: The major organs of the digestive system include the mouth, esophagus, stomach, and small and large in- testines.
Sent 6: These organs all work together to help you gain energy from the food you eat.
Sent 7: Digestion starts in the mouth.
Sent 8: When food is swallowed, it travels through the esophagus to the stomach.
Sent 9: In the stomach, digestion continues and a small amount of absorption of nutrients takes place.
Sent 10: Most chemical digestion and nearly all absorption of nutrients take place in the small intestine.
Sent 11: This organ consists of three parts: duodenum, jejunum, and ileum.
Sent 12: The large intestine is the last stop in the digestive system.
Sent 13: This is where water is absorbed.
Sent 14: The food not digested is released as waste.
Answer.Answer-1: It starts at the mouth and includes the esophagus, stomach, small and large intestine.
Answer.Answer-2: in the stomach but mostly in the intestines
Answer.Answer-3: water is absorbed and food is eliminated as waste
Answer.Question-1: What organs make up the digestive system and where does it start?
Answer.Question-2: Where does the absorption part of digestion occur?
Answer.Question-3: What happens to the food and water in the large intestine?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.

Sent 2: Do you know how long your digestive tract is?

Sent 4: This distance is needed to process the food you eat.
Sent 5: The food that is not digested is passed as waste.
Sent 6: The organs in the digestive tract are covered by a special type of muscle.
Sent 7: These muscles contract to help move the food along.
Sent 8: This muscle movement is like a wave through a spring toy.
Sent 9: Think about when you brush your teeth.
Sent 10: You squeeze the toothpaste from the tube.
Sent 11: The toothpaste moves out of the tube.
Sent 12: This action is similar to how food is passed through your digestive tract.
Sent 13: The diagram in Figure 3.8 shows how this process works.
Answer.Answer-1: a tube inside the body more than 30 feet in length where your food is digested.
Answer.Answer-2: they contract like a wave to move the food
Answer.Answer-3: a spring toy or a tube of toothpaste
Answer.Question-1: What is the digestive system and how much distance does it cover?
Answer.Question-2: How do the muscles of the digestive system work?
Answer.Question-3: What objects are similar to the way the muscles of the digestive system work?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Gravity can pull soil, mud, and rocks down cliffs and hillsides.
Sent 2: This is called mass movement.
Sent 3: The most destructive types of mass movement are landslides and mudslides.
Sent 4: They occur suddenly.
Sent 5: They generally have little warning before they happen.
Sent 6: They engulf everything in their path.
Sent 7: Two other types of mass movement are slump and creep.
Sent 8: They usually arent as destructive as landslides and mudslides.
Sent 9: Slump is the sudden movement of large blocks of rock and soil down a slope.
Sent 10: Creep is the very slow movement of rock and soil down a slope.
Sent 11: It causes trees, fence posts, and other structures to tilt downhill.
Answer.Answer-1: It is called mass movement.
Answer.Answer-2: Landslide is more dangerous
Answer.Answer-3: Creep
Answer.Question-1: What is the term for when gravity pulls soil?
Answer.Question-2: Which one is more dangerous, a landslide or a slump?
Answer.Question-3: Which mass movement occurrs slowly and can knock over fence posts?
Answer.Question-4: When does a landslide occur?
Answer.Question-5: What type of mass movement occurrs suddenly but not as dangerous as a landslide?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Speed is an important aspect of motion.
Sent 2: It is a measure of how fast or slow something moves.
Sent 3: To determine speed you must know two things.
Sent 4: First, you must know how far something travels.
Sent 5: Second, you need to know how long it takes to travel that far.
Sent 6: Speed can be calculated using this formula: speed = distance time A familiar example is the speed of a car.
Sent 7: In the U.S., this is usually expressed in miles per hour (see Figure 1.46).
Sent 8: Think about a trip you and your family made in the car.
Sent 9: Maybe the trip covered 120 miles and it took 3 hours.
Sent 10: What was the cars speed?
Sent 11: speed = 120 mi = 40 mi/h 3h The speed of a car may also be expressed in kilometers per hour (km/h).
Sent 12: The SI unit for speed is meters per second (m/s).
Sent 13: This is the unit of measure a scientist would use.
Answer.Answer-1: an aspect of motion, it is the measure of how slow or fast something travels
Answer.Answer-2: how far an object travels and how long it takes to get that far
Answer.Answer-3: speed=distance time, in miles per hour
Answer.Question-1: what is speed?
Answer.Question-2: How do you determine speed?
Answer.Question-3: How do you calculate speed in the U.S.?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.

Sent 2: It is a measure of how fast or slow something moves.
Sent 3: To determine speed you must know two things.
Sent 4: First, you must know how far something travels.
Sent 5: Second, you need to know how long it takes to travel that far.
Sent 6: Speed can be calculated using this formula: speed = distance time A familiar example is the speed of a car.
Sent 7: In the U.S., this is usually expressed in miles per hour (see Figure 1.46).
Sent 8: Think about a trip you and your family made in the car.
Sent 9: Maybe the trip covered 120 miles and it took 3 hours.
Sent 10: What was the cars speed?
Sent 11: speed = 120 mi = 40 mi/h 3h The speed of a car may also be expressed in kilometers per hour (km/h).
Sent 12: The SI unit for speed is meters per second (m/s).
Sent 13: This is the unit of measure a scientist would use.
Answer.Answer-1: You must know how far something travels and how long it takes to travel that far.
Answer.Answer-2: Speed = 120 mi = 40 mi/h 3h The speed of a car may also be expressed in kilometers per hour (km/h).
Answer.Answer-3: In the U.S., this is usually expressed in miles per hour, and the SI unit for speed is meters per second (m/s).
Answer.Question-1: How does one determine speed?
Answer.Question-2: How would the speed of a trip covering 120 miles and taking 3 hours be calculated?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Relying on an animal to come by is risky.
Sent 2: A flower may have to wait a long time for the right animals to come by.
Sent 3: What if one never passes close enough to the flower?
Sent 4: Hoping the wind will blow is also risky for a plant.
Sent 5: What if the wind does not blow?
Sent 6: What if the blowing pollen does not land on another flower?
Sent 7: The wind could even blow the pollen over the ocean where it is wasted.
Sent 8: Giving free nectar is costly.
Sent 9: It is not a good use of the plants energy.
Sent 10: A plant uses a lot of energy to produce nectar.
Sent 11: Some animals may just drink the nectar.
Sent 12: They may not carry off any pollen in return.
Sent 13: To improve their chances, plants evolved special traits.
Sent 14: For example, they developed ways to hide their nectar.
Sent 15: Only certain animals were able to get at the plants hidden nectar.
Sent 16: These specific animals might be more likely to visit only flowers of the same species.
Sent 17: This was also a benefit for some animals.
Sent 18: Animals also evolved special traits to get to the nectar.
Answer.Answer-1: Relying on an animal and hoping the wind will blow
Answer.Answer-2: Some animals may just drink the nectar and not carry off any pollen in return.
Answer.Answer-3: Only certain animals were able to get at the plant's hidden nectar because these specific animals might be more likely to visit only flowers of the same species.
Answer.Question-1: What are ways of transferring pollen?
Answer.Question-2: What might some animals do with a plant?
Answer.Question-3: What is the purpose of hidden nectar?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Flowers have both male and female reproductive parts.
Sent 2: The main parts of a flower are shown in Figure 3.21.
Sent 3: They include the stamen, pistil, petals, and sepals.
Sent 4: The stamen is the male reproductive structure of a flower.
Sent 5: It consists of a stalk-like filament.
Sent 6: At the end of the filament is the anther.
Sent 7: The anther contains pollen sacs.
Sent 8: It is here the pollen grains form.
Sent 9: The filament raises the anther up high.
Sent 10: This helps the pollen to be more likely to be carried away.
Sent 11: It may blow in the wind.
Sent 12: It may be picked up by an animal and carried away.
Sent 13: Many animals are pollinators.
Sent 14: A pollinator is any animal who carries the pollen from one plant to another.
Sent 15: The pistil is the female reproductive structure of a flower.
Sent 16: It consists of a stigma, style, and ovary.
Sent 17: The stigma is raised.
Sent 18: It is also sticky to help catch pollen.
Answer.Answer-1: pistil, petals, sepals, and stamen, which is the make reproductive part.
Answer.Answer-2: blown in the wind or carried off by an animal.
Answer.Answer-3: the pistil, which contains the style, ovary, and stigma.
Answer.Question-1: What are some if the parts of a flower and which is the name reproductive part?
Answer.Question-2: How is pollen spread?
Answer.Question-3: What is the female reproductive structure of a flower?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Almost all the things we do in our lives we have learned how to do.
Sent 2: Learned behavior is something animals do only after having done it or having practiced it.
Sent 3: For an animal, learning something may be better than having a natural ability.
Sent 4: A learned behavior is flexible.
Sent 5: This means that if the rules change you can quickly adapt.
Sent 6: If you were an animal in the wild, you could learn how to find food in different areas.
Sent 7: Here is one example of a learned behavior.
Sent 8: It also demonstrates why learned behaviors may be better than innate ability.
Sent 9: Innate ability is a trait you are born with.
Sent 10: You may walk each day from your house to school and back.
Sent 11: On your first day of school, did you know how to get there?
Sent 12: Of course not, it was learned.
Sent 13: Now assume your family has moved.
Sent 14: You may be a couple of streets over and a little further away.
Sent 15: You now have to take a different route to school.
Sent 16: What if following the old route was an innate behavior?
Sent 17: You would not be able to adapt.
Sent 18: You would not be able to find your way from the new house.
Answer.Answer-1: A learned behavior is repeated after having done it or practiced it while an innate ability  is a trait you are born with.
Answer.Answer-2: They are behaviors that are done or practiced in order to learn and they are flexible or can be releanred or changed if needed.
Answer.Answer-3: They allow one to adapt to new circumstances and are flexible and open to change via learning or practicing.
Answer.Question-1: What is the difference between a learned behavior and an innate ability?
Answer.Question-2: What are characteristics of learned behaviors?
Answer.Question-3: What are some advantages of learned behaviors?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Rock layers extend laterally, or out to the sides.
Sent 2: They may cover very large areas.
Sent 3: This is especially true if they formed at the bottom of ancient seas.
Sent 4: Seas are very large areas of water.
Sent 5: Over time, sediment builds up on the seabed.
Sent 6: They will be covered with the same types of material.
Sent 7: As rocks form out of this sediment it will all be the same type.
Sent 8: The rocks may be forced up above the water as Earths plates move.
Sent 9: Rivers may eventually run across this area.
Sent 10: The river will cut into the rock and erode it away.
Sent 11: The layers of exposed rock on either side of the river will still match up.
Sent 12: Look at the Grand Canyon in Figure 2.27.
Sent 13: Its a good example of lateral continuity.
Sent 14: You can clearly see the same rock layers on opposite sides of the canyon.
Sent 15: The matching rock layers were deposited at the same time.
Sent 16: They are the same age.
Answer.Answer-1: lateral continuity
Answer.Answer-2: Rivers may eventually run across this area
Answer.Answer-3: if they are formed at the bottom of ancient seas
Answer.Question-1: What is the Grand Canyon a good example of ?
Answer.Question-2: When rocks are forced up above the water as Earth plates move what may eventually happen ?
Answer.Question-3: When are rock layers more likely to cover large areas ?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Magnets are able to place a force on certain materials.
Sent 2: This force is called a magnetic force.
Sent 3: The force a magnet exerts is a little different from the forces you may normally think about.
Sent 4: You exert a force on a book when you lift it.
Sent 5: You also exert a force on the pedals of your bicycle.
Sent 6: In both those cases, those forces cause a change.
Sent 7: The change you see in both these cases is called motion.
Sent 8: Magnets, too, can produce change.
Sent 9: They can produce motion just like you do.
Sent 10: Unlike you, magnets do not have to touch something to exert a force.
Sent 11: A magnetic force is exerted over a distance.
Sent 12: Thats right, a magnet can push or pull certain items without ever touching them.
Sent 13: Thats how the maglev train works.

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Here is a riddle for you to ponder: What do you and a tiny speck of dust in outer space have in common?
Sent 2: Think you know the answer?
Sent 3: Both you and the speck of dust consist of matter.
Sent 4: So does the ground beneath your feet.
Sent 5: In fact, everything you can see and touch is made of matter.
Sent 6: The only things that are not matter are forms of energy.
Sent 7: This would include things such as light and sound.
Sent 8: Although forms of energy are not matter, the air and other substances they travel through are.
Sent 9: So what is matter?
Sent 10: Matter is defined as anything that has mass and volume.
Sent 11: You may recall that atoms are the building blocks of matter.
Sent 12: Even things as small as atoms have mass and volume.
Sent 13: The more atoms, or matter, the more mass and volume are present.
Sent 14: Different types of atoms have different amounts of mass and volume.
Sent 15: So, its not enough to know the count of atoms to determine the mass.
Sent 16: You must also know the type of atoms an item is made of.
Sent 17: Mass and volume are just two ways to describe the physical property of a substance.
Sent 18: Physical properties are all determined by the amounts and type of atoms that compose items.
Answer.Answer-1: Forms of energy
Answer.Answer-2: Anything that has mass and volume.
Answer.Answer-3: Atoms
Answer.Answer-4: The type of atoms an item is made of
Answer.Question-1: What is not made of matter if everything you can see and touch is made up of matter?
Answer.Question-2: What is matter?
Answer.Question-3: What is small that has mass and volume and is a building block fro matter?
Answer.Question-4: What else does one need to know if it is not enough to know the count of atoms to determine the mass?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: If you have a mass of 50 kg on Earth, what is your weight in newtons?
Sent 2: An object with more mass is pulled by gravity with greater force.
Sent 3: Mass and weight are closely related.
Sent 4: However, the weight of an object can change if the force of gravity changes.
Sent 5: On Earth, the force of gravity is the same everywhere.
Sent 6: So how does the force of gravity change?
Sent 7: It doesnt if you stay on Earth.
Sent 8: What if we travel to another planet or moon in our solar system?
Sent 9: Look at the photo of astronaut Edwin E. Aldrin Jr. taken by fellow astronaut Neil Armstrong in the Figure ??.
Sent 10: They were the first humans to walk on the moon.
Sent 11: An astronaut weighs less on the moon than he would on Earth.
Sent 12: This is because the moons gravity is weaker than Earths.
Sent 13: The astronauts mass, on the other hand, did not change.
Sent 14: He still contained the same amount of matter on the moon as he did on Earth.
Sent 15: If the astronaut weighed 175 pounds on Earth, he would have weighed only 29 pounds on the moon.
Sent 16: If his mass on Earth was 80 kg, what would his mass have been on the moon?
Sent 17: [Figure 3]
Answer.Answer-1: Mass is the amount of matter and weight is the force of gravity on the object.
Answer.Answer-2: Edwin E. Aldrin Jr. and Neil Armstrong
Answer.Answer-3: Newtons
Answer.Question-1: What's the difference between weight and mass?
Answer.Question-2: Who are the astronaut that weighed less on the moon?
Answer.Question-3: This unit of measurement can be used instead of pounds. What is it?

Sent 1: An atom is the very smallest particle that still the elements properties.
Sent 2: All the atoms of an element are alike.
Sent 3: They are also different from the atoms of all other elements.
Sent 4: For example, atoms of gold are always the same.
Sent 5: It does not matter if they are found in a gold nugget or a gold ring (see Figure 1.4).
Sent 6: All gold atoms have the same structure and properties.
Sent 7: For example, all gold atoms contain 79 protons.
Sent 8: One of golds unique properties is that it is a great conductor of electricity.
Sent 9: Gold is a better conductor of electricity than copper.
Sent 10: Gold is more rare and expensive than copper.
Sent 11: Copper is used in house wiring.
Sent 12: Gold is far too expensive.
Answer.Answer-1: All atoms within gold have the same structure and properties regardless of their physical shape.
Answer.Answer-2: Gold is a better conductor and more rare and expensive than Copper.
Answer.Answer-3: Copper wiring is used in houses because even though gold would conduct electricity better it is far to rare and expensive.
Answer.Answer-4: Atoms are the smallest units that contain elemental properties therefore, all atoms within one element are expressly alike to each other but different from those of another element.
Answer.Answer-5: Gold no matter what form is composed of atoms that contain the same elemental properties including the same structure, same properties and same number of protons.
Answer.Question-1: How are all the atoms of gold alike?
Answer.Question-2: What are the major differences between Gold and Copper?
Answer.Question-3: Why is copper used in house wiring even though Gold is a better conductor of electricity?
Answer.Question-4: Why are atoms in one element different from those in another element?
Answer.Question-5: Why would a gold ring and a gold nugget have the same properties?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: The properties of matter depend on the types of atoms that matter is made of.
Sent 2: Matter can exist in two forms.
Sent 3: It can be a pure substance.
Sent 4: This means it is not mixed with anything.
Sent 5: It can also be a combination of different substances.
Sent 6: This means it can be a mix of different types of atoms.
Sent 7: You may recall that atoms differ based on the numbers of protons they contain.
Sent 8: Some atoms contain only one proton such as Hydrogen.
Sent 9: Other atoms contain many protons.
Sent 10: There are many types of atoms.
Sent 11: For example, Helium has two protons.
Sent 12: An Oxygen atom has eight.
Sent 13: Water is composed of a two types of atoms.
Sent 14: Water is made of two Hydrogen atoms and one Oxygen atoms.
Sent 15: There are only so many types of atoms.
Sent 16: These atoms can be mixed into an almost limitless amount of substances.
Sent 17: So what do we call a substance that has only a single type of atom?
Answer.Answer-1: pure substance and a combination of different substances
Answer.Answer-2: means it is not mixed with anything
Answer.Answer-3: Water is made of two Hydrogen atoms and one Oxygen atoms.
Answer.Question-1: What two forms of matter are there?
Answer.Question-2: What does pure substance mean?
Answer.Question-3: Water is composed of which two atoms?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Roots are important organs in most modern plants.
Sent 2: There are two types of roots.
Sent 3: First, there are the primary roots, which grow downward.
Sent 4: Secondly, there are the secondary roots.
Sent 5: These roots branch out to the sides.
Sent 6: Together, all the roots of a plant make up the plants root system.
Sent 7: Figure 3.2 shows two different types of plant root systems.
Sent 8: A taproot system has a very long primary root, called a taproot.
Sent 9: A fibrous root system has many smaller roots and no large, primary root.
Sent 10: The roots of plants have three major jobs.
Sent 11: They must absorb water and minerals, anchor and support the plant, and store food.
Sent 12: Roots have special features that are well suited to absorb water and dissolved minerals from the soil.
Sent 13: Root systems help anchor plants to the ground.
Sent 14: They allow plants to grow tall without falling over.
Sent 15: In many plants, roots store food produced by the leaves.
Sent 16: This process is called photosynthesis.
Answer.Answer-1: Primary and secondary roots.
Answer.Answer-2: Absorb water and minerals, anchor the plant, and store food.
Answer.Answer-3: Photosynthesis.
Answer.Answer-4: A taproot system has a long primary root where the fiberous root system has many smaller roots and no large primary root.
Answer.Answer-5: This allows the plant to grow tall without falling over.
Answer.Question-1: What are the two types of roots?
Answer.Question-2: Of these two types of roots, what are their three major jobs?
Answer.Question-3: What is the process called whereby plants store food produced by the leaves?
Answer.Question-4: What is the difference between a taproot root system and a fiberous root system?
Answer.Question-5: Why do root systems need to anchor the plant to the ground?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Leaves are the keys not only to plant life but to virtually all life on land.
Sent 2: The primary role of leaves is to collect sunlight.
Sent 3: This sunlight is needed for the plant to make food.
Sent 4: Leaves vary in size, shape, and how they are arranged on stems.
Sent 5: You can see examples of different types of leaves in Figure 3.4.
Sent 6: Each type of leaf is well suited for the plants environment.
Sent 7: It maximizes light exposure while conserving water.
Sent 8: They are also reduces wind resistance.
Sent 9: Leaves also benefit the plant in some other way in its particular habitat.
Sent 10: For example, some leaves are divided into many smaller leaflets.
Sent 11: This reduces wind resistance and water loss.
Sent 12: Leaves are basically factories for photosynthesis.
Sent 13: A factory has specialized machines to produce a product.
Sent 14: In a leaf, the \machines\ are the chloroplasts.
Sent 15: A factory is connected to a transportation system that supplies it with raw materials and carries away the finished product.
Sent 16: In a leaf, transport is carried out by veins containing vascular tissue.
Sent 17: Veins carry water and minerals to the cells of leaves.
Sent 18: They carry away dissolved sugar.
Answer.Answer-1: Leaves are the key to virtually all life on land and benefit the plants in their particular habitats.
Answer.Answer-2: carry water and minerals, carry away dissolved sugar
Answer.Answer-3: Maximizes light exposure while conserving water, reducing wind resistance.
Answer.Question-1: What is very special about leaves?
Answer.Question-2: What do the veins do?
Answer.Question-3: How does each leaf being suited to their particular habitat do?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Temperate climates have moderate temperatures.
Sent 2: These climates vary in how much rain they get and when the rain falls.
Sent 3: You can see different types of temperate climates in Figure 2.40.
Sent 4: Mediterranean climates are found on the western coasts of continents.
Sent 5: The coast of California has a Mediterranean climate.
Sent 6: Temperatures are mild and rainfall is moderate.
Sent 7: Most of the rain falls in the winter, and summers are dry.
Sent 8: To make it through the dry summers, short woody plants are common.
Sent 9: Marine west coast climates are also found on the western coasts of continents.
Sent 10: The coast of Washington State has this type of climate.
Sent 11: Temperatures are mild and theres plenty of rainfall all year round.
Sent 12: Dense fir forests grow in this climate.
Sent 13: Humid subtropical climates are found on the eastern sides of continents.
Sent 14: The southeastern U.S. has this type of climate.
Sent 15: Summers are hot and humid, but winters are chilly.
Sent 16: There is moderate rainfall throughout the year.
Sent 17: Pine and oak forests grow in this climate.
Answer.Answer-1: Temperatures are mild, rainfalls are moderate, rain falls mostly in the winters and summers are dry.
Answer.Answer-2: They are humid,summers are hot and humid, winters are chilly and there is moderate rainfall through out the year.
Answer.Answer-3: A lot of short woody plants grow in a Mediterranian climate while pines and oaks prefer a Subtropical climate.
Answer.Question-1: What are characteristics of a Mediterranean Climate:?
Answer.Question-2: What are some characteristics of Subtopical climates?
Answer.Question-3: How do the main plants differ between a Mediterranian climate and a Subtropical climate?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Why isnt the climate of an area only impacted by its latitude?
Sent 2: How can oceans and mountain ranges have such an impact on local climate types?
Sent 3: Read on to find out more.
Sent 4: Florida is at the same latitude as North Africa.
Sent 5: North Africa contains the worlds largest desert.
Sent 6: Following the line of latitude to the west, you can also find arid climates.
Sent 7: West Texas, Mexico, and the Baja Peninsula of California are all arid climates.
Sent 8: These areas fall along the same latitude and within the temperate climate zone.
Sent 9: How can they have such a diverse local climate?
Sent 10: Think about where Florida is located.
Sent 11: It is a long sliver of land mostly surrounded by water.
Sent 12: It is much smaller than North Africa.
Sent 13: It is wider than the Baja Peninsula in Mexico.
Sent 14: Florida is very wet and the other two locations are extremely arid.
Sent 15: It just so happens the size of Florida is just right for the development of thunderstorms.
Sent 16: The Baja Peninsula is too narrow to cause such a weather effect.
Sent 17: North Africa is far too large.
Sent 18: In this case it was the size of land and proximity to water that made the difference.
Answer.Answer-1: Latitude and oceans and mountain ranges.
Answer.Answer-2: They are all arid climates and fall along the same latitude and within the temperate climate zone.
Answer.Answer-3: Florida is very wet and the other two locations are extremely arid and it just so happens the size of Florida is just right for the development of thunderstorms, but the Baja Peninsula is too narrow to cause such a weather effect.
Answer.Question-1: What impacts a climate?
Answer.Question-2: How are West Texas, Mexico, and the Baja Peninsula similar?
Answer.Question-3: How is Florida different from Baja California?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Continental climates are found in inland areas.
Sent 2: They are too far from oceans to experience the effects of ocean water.
Sent 3: Continental climates are common between 40 and 70 north latitude.
Sent 4: There are no continental climates in the Southern Hemisphere.
Sent 5: Can you guess why?
Sent 6: The southern continents at this latitude are too narrow.
Sent 7: All of their inland areas are close enough to a coast to be affected by the ocean!
Sent 8: Humid continental climates get plenty of precipitation year round.
Sent 9: The northeastern U.S. has this type of climate.
Sent 10: Summers are warm to hot, and winters are cold.
Sent 11: Deciduous trees grow in this climate.
Sent 12: They lose their leaves in the fall and grow new ones in the spring.
Sent 13: Subarctic climates have cool and short summers.
Sent 14: Winters are long and cold.
Sent 15: Much of Canada and Alaska have this type of climate.
Sent 16: Little precipitation falls, and most of it falls during the summer.
Sent 17: Conifer forests grow in this climate (see Figure 2.41).
Answer.Answer-1: various inland continental climates around the world
Answer.Answer-2: They have cool short summers and long cold winters. Alaska and Canada.
Answer.Answer-3: the continents at that latitude are too narrow and their inland areas are cl lose enough to be affected by the ocean.
Answer.Question-1: What is the topic of the paragraph?
Answer.Question-2: What are subartic climates and where can you find them?
Answer.Question-3: Why don't continental climates exist in the southern hemisphere?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: There are basically three climate zones around the world: polar, temperate, and tropical.
Sent 2: Each climate zone has unique traits.
Sent 3: They are located in specific latitudes.
Sent 4: Polar zones often have long, very cold winters.
Sent 5: They have short, cool summers.
Sent 6: Very cold air masses from the arctic often move in.
Sent 7: The temperature range is larger than any other climate.
Sent 8: Precipitation increases during summer months.
Sent 9: Annual precipitation amounts are still small.
Sent 10: Tropical zones are often warmer areas.
Sent 11: They tend to have an abundance of rainfall.
Sent 12: These are generally located near the equator.
Sent 13: Temperate zones fall between the polar and the tropical zones.
Sent 14: They tend to have milder climate conditions than both tropical and polar.
Sent 15: You might expect places near the equator to be hot and wet.
Sent 16: Thats not always the case.
Sent 17: Sometimes there are other factors at work.
Sent 18: These factors can affect the local climate type or a region.
Answer.Answer-1: long cold winters, short cool summers
Answer.Answer-2: near the equator
Answer.Answer-3: warmer, abundance of rainfall
Answer.Question-1: What are some attributes of polar climate zones?
Answer.Question-2: Where are tropical climate zones usually located?
Answer.Question-3: What are some traits of tropical climate zones

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Water keeps changing state as it goes through the water cycle.
Sent 2: This means that it can be a solid, liquid, or gas.
Sent 3: How does water change state?
Sent 4: How does it keep moving through the cycle?
Sent 5: As Figure 2.3 shows, several processes are involved.
Sent 6: Evaporation changes liquid water to water vapor.
Sent 7: Energy from the sun causes water to evaporate.
Sent 8: Most evaporation is from the oceans because they cover so much area.
Sent 9: The water vapor rises into the atmosphere.
Sent 10: Transpiration is like evaporation because it changes liquid water to water vapor.
Sent 11: In transpiration, plants release water vapor through their leaves.
Sent 12: This water vapor rises into the atmosphere.
Sent 13: Condensation changes water vapor to liquid water.
Sent 14: As air rises higher into the atmosphere, it cools.
Sent 15: Cool air can hold less water vapor than warm air.
Sent 16: So some of the water vapor condenses into water droplets.
Sent 17: Water droplets may form clouds.
Sent 18: Precipitation is water that falls from clouds to Earths surface.
Answer.Answer-1: yes into liquid,solid or gas
Answer.Answer-2: plants release water vapor through their leaves
Answer.Answer-3: evaporation, transpiration, and condensation
Answer.Question-1: Does water change states?
Answer.Question-2: What happens during transpiration?
Answer.Question-3: How does water change states?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph

Sent 9: The rising air cools as it goes higher in the atmosphere.
Sent 10: If it is moist, the water vapor may condense.

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Clouds are classified on the basis of where and how they form.
Sent 2: Three main types of clouds are cirrus, stratus, and cumulus.
Sent 3: Figure 2.25 shows these and other types of clouds.
Sent 4: Cirrus clouds form high in the troposphere.
Sent 5: Because it is so cold they are made of ice crystals.
Sent 6: They are thin and wispy.
Sent 7: Cirrus clouds dont usually produce precipitation, but they may be a sign that wet weather is coming.
Sent 8: Stratus clouds occur low in the troposphere.
Sent 9: They form in layers that spread horizontally and may cover the entire sky like a thick blanket.
Sent 10: Stratus clouds that produce precipitation are called nimbostratus.
Sent 11: The prefix nimbo- means rain.
Sent 12: Cumulus clouds are white and puffy.
Sent 13: Convection currents make them grow upward and they may grow very tall.
Sent 14: When they produce rain, they are called cumulonimbus.
Answer.Answer-1: Cirrus, stratus, cumulus. They're named based off where and how they form.
Answer.Answer-2: cumulonimbus and nimbostratus
Answer.Answer-3: cirrus
Answer.Question-1: What are the three main types of clouds and how are they classified?
Answer.Question-2: What are two kinds of cloud that produce rain?
Answer.Question-3: Which clouds are thin, wispy, and usually made of ice crystals?

Sent 11: The prefix nimbo- means rain.
Sent 12: Cumulus clouds are white and puffy.
Sent 13: Convection currents make them grow upward and they may grow very tall.
Sent 14: When they produce rain, they are called cumulonimbus.

Answer.Answer-2: Cumulus and cumulonimbus.
Answer.Answer-3: Convection currents make them grow upward and they may grow very tall, then they produce rain.
Answer.Answer-4: Cirrus clouds form high in the troposphere, it is so cold they form ice crystals.
Answer.Answer-5: All stratus clouds cover the entire sky like a thick blanket. Some stratus clouds produce precipitation and are called nimbostratus.
Answer.Question-1: How are the altitude of Stratus clouds and Cirrus clouds different?
Answer.Question-2: What are two versions of the rain cloud that is white and puffy?
Answer.Question-3: What does the life cycle of a cumulonimbus cloud entail?

Answer.Question-5: What are different types of stratus clouds?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Water shortages are common in much of the world.
Sent 2: People are most likely to run short of water during droughts.
Sent 3: A drought is a period of unusually low rainfall.
Sent 4: Human actions have increased how often droughts occur.
Sent 5: In some areas, humans have cut down all the trees.
Sent 6: This action can bring on a drought.
Sent 7: Trees add a lot of water vapor to the air.
Sent 8: With fewer trees, the air is drier and droughts are more common.
Sent 9: We use six times as much water today as we did a hundred years ago.
Sent 10: As the number of people rises, our need for water will grow.
Sent 11: By the year 2025, only half the worlds people will have enough clean water.
Sent 12: Water is a vital resource.
Sent 13: Water shortages may even lead to other problems.
Sent 14: Crops and livestock may die.
Sent 15: As a result, people will have less food available.
Sent 16: Other uses of water, such as industry, may have to stop.
Sent 17: This reduces the number of jobs available to people of that area.
Sent 18: People and nations may fight over water resources.
Answer.Answer-1: Because water is "vital" and shortages cause problems such as food shortages and loss of jobs, which people need to survive.
Answer.Answer-2: Because trees add water vapor to the air.  Less trees means less water vapor.
Answer.Answer-3: Stop cutting down trees and add new trees in places previously cut down.  This will maintain proper levels of water vapor in the air and reduce the chances of drought.
Answer.Question-1: Why would people and nations fight over water resources?
Answer.Question-2: Why does the number of trees in an area affect how dry the air is and lead to the likeliness of drought?
Answer.Question-3: What can people do to reduce the likelihood of drought?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Living things need non-living matter as well as energy.
Sent 2: What do you think matter is used for?
Sent 3: One thing is to build bodies.
Sent 4: They also need it to carry out the processes of life.
Sent 5: Any non-living matter that living things need is called a nutrient.
Sent 6: Carbon and nitrogen are examples of nutrients.
Sent 7: Unlike energy, matter is recycled in ecosystems.
Sent 8: You can see how in Figure 3.11.
Sent 9: Decomposers release nutrients when they break down dead organisms.
Sent 10: The nutrients are taken up by plants through their roots.
Sent 11: The nutrients pass to primary consumers when they eat the plants.
Sent 12: The nutrients pass to higher level consumers when they eat lower level consumers.
Sent 13: When living things die, the cycle repeats.
Answer.Answer-1: Build bodies
Answer.Answer-2: Carbon and nitrogen
Answer.Answer-3: Dead organisms decompose and release nutrients
Answer.Question-1: What is one thing non-living matter used for?
Answer.Question-2: Non-living matter in living things is called nutrients and a couple of these nutrients are what?
Answer.Question-3: What happens so plants can take nutrients in through their roots?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Have you are burned something on the stove or in the oven?
Sent 2: Do you know why things burn?
Sent 3: It all has to do with temperature.
Sent 4: Changes in matter are affected by temperature.
Sent 5: For example, what if you place a cake in the oven and you leave it in too long?
Sent 6: What do you think will happen?
Sent 7: Thats right, it will probably burn.
Sent 8: The same thing will happen if the oven setting is too high and you apply too much heat.
Sent 9: In either case, heat has affected the rate of change in matter.
Sent 10: Its probably obvious that when the temperature is increased a chemical change, like cooking, will occur faster.
Sent 11: What about a physical change?
Sent 12: Are physical changes affected by temperature?
Sent 13: Most of us have seen steam rising off a wet road after a summer rainstorm.
Sent 14: This happens because the road surface is very warm.
Sent 15: The warm road and warm air temperature causes the water to evaporate quickly.
Sent 16: The liquid water is turning into water vapor, but it is still water.
Sent 17: The evaporation of water is a physical change.
Sent 18: So yes, temperature affects the rate that physical change occurs.
Answer.Answer-1: It will burn.
Answer.Answer-2: Temperature
Answer.Answer-3: Change in matter and physical change
Answer.Question-1: What can happen if you place a cake in an oven and apply too much heat or set the oven heat too high?
Answer.Question-2: What can cause a physical change to water?
Answer.Question-3: What kind of changes can be caused by temperature?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: If you build a campfire, you start with a large stack of sticks and logs.
Sent 2: As the fire burns, the stack slowly shrinks.
Sent 3: By the end of the evening, all that is left is a small pile of ashes.
Sent 4: What happened to the matter that you started with?
Sent 5: Was it destroyed by the flames?
Sent 6: It may seem that way.
Sent 7: What do you think happened?
Sent 8: The truth is that the same amount of matter still exists.
Sent 9: The wood changed not only to ashes, but also to carbon dioxide, water vapor, and other gases.
Sent 10: The gases floated off into the air, leaving behind just the ashes.
Sent 11: Although matter was changed, it was not created or destroyed.
Sent 12: Because the same amount of matter still exists, we can say that matter is conserved.
Sent 13: You may wonder how it can be conserved if something is now missing?
Sent 14: Assume you had measured the mass of the wood before you burned it.
Sent 15: Assume you had also trapped the gases released by the burning wood and measured their mass and the mass of the ashes.
Sent 16: What would you find?
Sent 17: The ashes and gases combined have the same mass as the wood you started with.
Sent 18: This example illustrates the law of conservation of mass.
Answer.Answer-1: The stack of sticks.
Answer.Answer-2: The law of conservation of mass.
Answer.Answer-3: The wood changed to carbon dioxide, water vapor, and other gases that floated off into the air, leaving behind just the ashes.
Answer.Question-1: As a fire burns, what stack slowly shrinks?
Answer.Question-2: The fact that ashes and gases combined have the same mass as the wood you started with illustrates what law?
Answer.Question-3: What happened to the matter changed to when burning a fire?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Chemical changes produce new substances.
Sent 2: For this reason, they often cannot be undone.
Sent 3: Some chemical changes can be reversed, sort of.
Sent 4: To do so requires another chemical change to take place.
Sent 5: For example, you can undo the tarnish on copper pennies by placing them in vinegar.
Sent 6: The acid in the vinegar reacts with the tarnish.
Sent 7: This is a chemical change that makes the pennies bright and shiny again.
Sent 8: You can try this yourself at home to see how well it works.
Sent 9: Other chemical changes cannot be reversed at all or may be difficult to do.
Sent 10: Rusting is a chemical change.
Sent 11: If metal rusts, the best you can do is to sand off the rust to get down to the shiny metal.
Sent 12: Although the metal may now be shiny, the rust was removed.
Sent 13: The rust was not changed back into the original metal.
Sent 14: Some chemical reactions occur in only one direction.
Sent 15: These reactions are called irreversible reactions.
Sent 16: For example, you cannot change a fried egg back into a raw egg.
Sent 17: Can you think of some other irreversible reactions related to cooking?
Sent 18: Would you like a piece of cake?
Answer.Answer-1: You can use vinegar to remove the tarnishes by causing another chemical change when they react.
Answer.Answer-2: Not really, but you can create a new chemical change that will bring the substance back to its previous state.
Answer.Answer-3: change a fried egg back into a raw egg, or unbaking cake
Answer.Question-1: What can you do to make pennies bright and shiny again?
Answer.Question-2: Can chemical changes be undone?
Answer.Question-3: What are some examples of irreversible reactions?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph

Sent 4: During a partial lunar eclipse, only a portion of the Moon enters Earths umbra.
Sent 5: When the Moon passes through Earths penumbra, it is a penumbral eclipse.
Sent 6: Since Earths shadow is large, a lunar eclipse lasts for hours.
Sent 7: Anyone with a view of the Moon can see a lunar eclipse.
Sent 8: So unlike a solar eclipse, it doesnt get dark on Earth.
Sent 9: Instead it gets dark on the Moon.
Sent 10: Partial lunar eclipses occur at least twice a year, but total lunar eclipses are less common.
Sent 11: The Moon glows with a dull red coloring during a total lunar eclipse.
Answer.Answer-1: total- the moon travels completely in Earth's umbra, partial- only a portion of the moon enters the Earth's umbra
Answer.Answer-2: It doesn't get dark on Earth but instead gets dark on the moon and can be seem from anywhere on the Earth.
Answer.Answer-3: Less often than partial lunar eclipse which happen at least twice a year and the moon glows a dull red.
Answer.Question-1: What is the difference between a total lunar eclipse and a partial lunar eclipse?
Answer.Question-2: How is a lunar eclipse different from a solar eclipse?
Answer.Question-3: How often does total lunar eclipse occur and what color is the moon?
