Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Reducing resource use means just what it says using fewer resources.
Sent 2: There are lots of ways to reduce our use of resources.
Sent 3: Buy durable goods.
Sent 4: Choose items that are well made so they will last longer.
Sent 5: Youll buy fewer items in the long run, so youll save money as well as resources.
Sent 6: Thats a win-win!
Sent 7: Repair rather than replace.
Sent 8: Fix your bike rather than buying a new one.
Sent 9: Sew on a button instead of buying a new shirt.
Sent 10: Youll use fewer resources and save money.
Sent 11: Buy only what you need.
Sent 12: Dont buy a gallon of milk if you can only drink half of it before it spoils.
Sent 13: Instead, buy a half gallon and drink all of it.
Sent 14: You wont be wasting resources (or money!) Buy local.
Sent 15: For example, buy local produce at a farmers market, like the one in Figure 2.20.
Sent 16: A lot of resources are saved by not shipping goods long distances.
Sent 17: Products bought at farmers markets use less packaging, too!
Sent 18: About a third of what we throw out is packaging.
Answer.Answer-1: Buy durable goods, repair rather than replace, buy only what you need, buy local.
Answer.Answer-2: A lot of resources are saved by not shipping goods long distances and many products bought at farmers markets use less money.
Answer.Answer-3: The products will last longer and you'll buy fewer items in the long run.
Answer.Answer-4: You save money as well as resources
Answer.Question-1: What are some general ways to reduce the use of resources?
Answer.Question-2: How can you reduce the use of resources by buying local?
Answer.Question-3: How does buying durable items save resources?
Answer.Question-4: How is it a win-win to buy durable goods?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: Renewable resources can be renewed as they are used.
Sent 2: An example is timber, which comes from trees.
Sent 3: New trees can be planted to replace those that are cut down.
Sent 4: Sunlight is a renewable resource.
Sent 5: It seems we will never run out of that!
Sent 6: Just because a resource is renewable, it doesnt mean we should use it carelessly.
Sent 7: If we arent careful, we can pollute resources.
Sent 8: Then they may no longer be fit for use.
Sent 9: Water is one example.
Sent 10: If we pollute a water source it may not be usable for drinking, bathing, or any other type of use.
Sent 11: We can also overuse resources that should be renewable.
Sent 12: In this case, the resources may not be able to recover.
Sent 13: For example, fish are renewable resources.
Sent 14: Thats because they can reproduce and make more fish.
Sent 15: But water pollution and overfishing can cause them to die out if their population becomes too low.
Sent 16: Figure 2.16 shows another example.
Answer.Answer-1: Timber and sunlight.
Answer.Answer-2: Water is one example since if we pollute a water source it may not be usable for drinking, bathing, or any other type of use.
Answer.Answer-3: Fish are renewable resources but water pollution and overfishing can cause them to die out if their population becomes too low.
Answer.Question-1: What are some renewable resources?
Answer.Question-2: What is an example of polluting resources?
Answer.Question-3: How can we overuse resources that should be renewable?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: So what is gravity?
Sent 2: A typical definition of gravity is that it is a force.
Sent 3: It causes an attraction between two masses.
Sent 4: According to this definition, anything that has mass exerts a force.
Sent 5: Any object exerts gravity on other objects.
Sent 6: It does not matter how small it is, it has gravity.
Sent 7: The more matter an object has, the more gravity it has.
Sent 8: Your pencil has a tiny bit of gravity, but far too little to notice.
Sent 9: What about a planet?
Sent 10: It would have a lot of gravity.
Sent 11: An objects gravity exerts a pull on other objects.
Sent 12: Friction only occurs between objects that are touching.
Sent 13: Gravity can act between objects that are not touching.
Sent 14: In fact, gravity can act over very long distances.
Sent 15: Where else can you feel gravity?
Answer.Answer-1: Friction only occurs between objects that are touching. Gravity can act between objects that are not touching.
Answer.Answer-2: No. Big or small, every object exerts gravitational force.
Answer.Answer-3: yes
Answer.Question-1: How do gravity and friction differ?
Answer.Question-2: Does size matter as to whether or not an object has gravity?
Answer.Question-3: Would a planet have more gravity than a pencil?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: The idea that Earth is a magnet is far from new.
Sent 2: It was first proposed in 1600 by a British physician named William Gilbert.
Sent 3: Knowing it acts like a magnet is one thing.
Sent 4: Knowing why it acts like a magnet is more difficult.
Sent 5: In fact, finding out why is a fairly recent discovery.
Sent 6: To find out why required new technology.
Sent 7: It was the seismograph that made it possible to learn why the Earth acted like a magnet.
Sent 8: Seismograph are used to study earthquakes.
Sent 9: By studying earthquake waves they were able to learn about Earths interior (see Figure 1.35).
Sent 10: They discovered that Earth has an inner and outer core.
Sent 11: The outer core consists of liquid metals, mainly iron and nickel.
Sent 12: Scientists think that Earths magnetic field is generated here.
Sent 13: It is caused by the motion of this liquid metal.
Sent 14: The liquid metal moves as Earth spins on its axis.
Answer.Answer-1: We know it acts like a magnet but not why it acts like a magnet.
Answer.Answer-2: A seismograph made it possible to learn why the Earth acted like a magnet because by studying earthquake waves they were able to learn about Earth's interior.
Answer.Answer-3: Earth's magnetic field is generated in the outer core by the motion of this liquid metal.
Answer.Question-1: What do we know and don't about the Earth and magnets?
Answer.Question-2: How did they learn why the Earth acts like a magnet?
Answer.Question-3: How is the magnetic field generated?

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.
PARAGRAPH:
Sent 1: So how do we know that the Earth rotates on its axis?
Sent 2: Before this century, all evidence collected about Earths motion came from Earth-bound observations.
Sent 3: From Earth-bound observation it is easy to see why, historically, the Earth was stationary.
Sent 4: It was the Sun and the stars that orbited the Earth.
Sent 5: One simple experiment can be used to show that is not the case.
Sent 6: It is the Earth that is rotating causing the cycles we see in the sky.
Sent 7: The experiment was designed by Lon Foucault, a French scientist, in the year 1851.

Title: Creating Questions Given a Paragraph
Description: Given a (English) paragraph, generate questions which require multiple-sentences.

Sent 1: The Earth is tilted 23 1/2 on its axis.
Sent 2: This means that as the Earth rotates, one hemisphere has longer days with shorter nights.
Sent 3: At the same time the other hemisphere has shorter days and longer nights.
Sent 4: For example, in the Northern hemisphere summer begins on June 21.
Sent 5: On this date, the North Pole is pointed directly toward the Sun.
Sent 6: This is the longest day and shortest night of the year in the Northern Hemisphere.
Sent 7: The South Pole is pointed The hemisphere that is tilted away from the Sun is cooler because it receives fewer direct rays.
Sent 8: As Earth orbits the Sun, the Northern Hemisphere goes from winter to spring, then summer and fall.
Sent 9: The Southern Hemisphere does the opposite from summer to fall to winter to spring.
Sent 10: When it is winter in the Northern hemisphere, it is summer in the Southern hemisphere, and vice versa.
Sent 11: What does this mean for you?
Sent 12: If you live in North America, July 1 is usually a very warm day.
Sent 13: If you traveled to Southern Australia, you would need a heavy coat.
Sent 14: At the equator, the seasons never change.
Sent 15: As a result, the average daily temperatures remain the same.
Sent 16: There is no summer and winter as we know them.
Answer.Answer-1: On this date, the North Pole is pointed directly toward the Sun. This is the longest day and shortest night of the year in the Northern Hemisphere
Answer.Answer-2: as the Earth rotates, one hemisphere has longer days with shorter nights, the other hemisphere has shorter days and longer nights
Answer.Answer-3: Because equator is never tilted away or towards the sun to get fewer or more sun rays
Answer.Question-1: What is special about June 21?
Answer.Question-2: How does Earth tilting affect the lenth of days and nights?
Answer.Question-3: Why at the equator seasons do not change?
